<section xml:id="sec-Cayley-Hamilton">	<title>Cayley-Hamilton Theorem</title>	<introduction>We begin with the following observation.</introduction>	<observation>		Let <m>T\colon V\to V</m> be an <m>F</m>-linear map of a finite-dimensional vector space <m>V</m> over a field <m>F</m>. We denote by <m>T^k=\underbrace{T\circ T\circ\cdots\circ T}_{k-\text{times}}</m>. If <m>p(t)=a_0+a_1t+\cdots+a_nt^n\in F[t]</m> is a polynomial then <men xml:id="evaluating-at-T">a_0\unit_V+a_1T+\cdots+a_nT^n\in\End_F(V)</men>.	</observation>	<convention>		We denote by <m>p(T)\in\End_F(V)</m> the expression obtained in <xref ref="evaluating-at-T"/>.	</convention>	<observation>		If <m>s(t)=f(t)+g(t)\in F[t]</m> and <m>u(t)=f(t)g(t)\in F[t]</m> then we have the following.		<men xml:id="ev-sum">s(T)=f(T)+g(T)</men>		<men xml:id="ev-multiplication">u(T)=f(T)g(T)</men>		<men xml:id="ev-commutative">f(T)g(T)=g(T)f(T)</men>	</observation>	<definition xml:id="annihilator-of-T">		<title>(Annihilator of a linear map)</title>		A polynomial <m>p(t)\in F[t]</m> is said to <term>annihilate</term> a linear map <m>T</m> if <m>p(T)=0\in\End_F(V)</m>.	</definition>	<p>We show the existence of an annihilating polynomial.</p>	<lemma xml:id="existence-of-annihilating-polynomial">		<title>(Existence of an annihilating polynomial)</title>		<statement>Let <m>V</m> be a finite-dimensional vector space over a field <m>F</m> and let <m>T\colon V\to V</m> be an <m>F</m>-linear map. Then there exists a polynomial <m>p(t)\in F[t]</m> such that <m>p(T)=0\in\End_F(V)</m>.</statement>	</lemma>	<proof>		Let <m>\dim_FV=n</m>. By <xref ref="dim-of-matrices"/>, <m>\dim_F\End_F(V)=(\dim_FV)^2&lt;\infty</m>. Hence the subset <m>\{\unit_V,T,T^2,\ldots,T^n,\ldots,T^{n^2}\}</m> of <m>\End_F(V)</m> is linearly dependent, i.e., there are scalars <m>a_0,a_1,\ldots,a_{n^2}\in F</m>, not all zero, such that		<me>a_0\unit_V+a_1T+\cdots + a_{n^2}T^{n^2}=0\in\End_FV.</me> Hence the polynomial <m>p(t)=a_0+a_t+\cdots+a_{n^2}t^{n^2}\in F[t]</m> is an annihilating polynomial of <m>T</m>.	</proof>	<p>The Cayley-Hamilton theorem stated below asserts that there exists an annihilating polynomial of degree <m>\dim_FV</m>, namely, the characteristic polynomial of <m>T</m>.</p>	<theorem xml:id="Cayley-Hamilton-Theorem">		<title>(Cayley-Hamilton Theorem)</title>		<statement>			Let <m>V</m> be a finite-dimensional vector space over a field <m>F</m> and let <m>T\colon V\to V</m> be an <m>F</m>-linear map. The characteristic polynomial of <m>T</m> annihilates <m>T</m>.		</statement>	</theorem>		<exercise>		<statement>Verify Cayley-Hamilton Theorem for any square matrix of your choice.</statement>	</exercise>	<p>We will not give a proof of Cayley-Hamilton theorem. However, we prove  the theorem for triangulable linear maps.</p>	<proposition xml:id="Cayley-Hamilton-triangulable">		<title>(Cayley-Hamilton theorem for triangulable linear maps)</title>		<statement>			Let <m>V</m> be a finite-dimensional vector space over a field <m>F</m> and let <m>T\colon V\to V</m> be a triangulable <m>F</m>-linear map. Then <m>\chi_T(T)=0.</m>		</statement>	</proposition>	<proof>		By <xref ref="triangulable-criterion-ch-poly"/>, <m>\chi_T=(t-\lambda_1)(t-\lambda_2)\cdots(t-\lambda_n)\in F[t]</m> and thus, there exists a basis <m>\mathfrak{B}=\{v_1,v_2,\ldots,v_n\}</m> of <m>V</m> such that 		<me>[T]_{\mathfrak{B}}=\begin{pmatrix}\lambda_1\amp a_{12}\amp\cdots\amp a_{1n}\\0\amp \lambda_2\amp\cdots\amp a_{2n}\\\vdots\amp\vdots\amp\ddots\amp \vdots\\0\amp 0\amp\cdots\amp \lambda_n\end{pmatrix}.</me>		Hence, 		<men xml:id="matrix-representation">T(v_1)=\lambda_1v_1\quad\text{and}\quad T(v_k)=\sum_{\ell=1}^{k-1}a_{\ell k}v_\ell+\lambda_kv_k\quad\text{for}\;2\leq k\leq n.</men>		For any <m>\lambda_i</m> and <m>\lambda_j</m> we have <men xml:id="commutativity-particular">(T-\lambda_i\unit_V)(T-\lambda_j\unit_V)=(T-\lambda_j\unit_V)(T-\lambda_i\unit_V).</men>		For any <m>k\geq 1</m> put <m>g_{k}(T)=(T-\lambda_{k}\unit_V)(T-\lambda_{k-1}\unit_V)\cdots(T-\lambda_1\unit_V)</m>.		In particular <men xml:id="ch-poly-linear-factors">\chi_T(T)=g_{n}(T)=(T-\lambda_n\unit_V)(T-\lambda_{n-1}\unit_V)\cdots(T-\lambda_1\unit_V).</men> We can obtain the following identity by a repeated application of <xref ref="commutativity-particular"/>.		<men xml:id="commutativity-general">(T-\lambda_k\unit_V)\cdot g_{k-1}(T)=g_{k-1}(T)\cdot(T-\lambda_k\unit_V)</men>		We show that <m>\chi_T(T)(v_k)=0</m> for every basis vector <m>v_k</m>. We prove this by showing <m>g_{k}(T)(v_i)=0</m> for every <m>1\leq i\leq k</m> and <m>1\leq k\leq n</m>. We have <m>(T-\lambda_1\unit_V)(v_1)=0</m>. Hence, by <xref ref="commutativity-general"/>, <m>g_k(T)(v_1)=0</m> for all <m>k</m>. Now assume that, for some <m>1\lt r-1\lt n</m>, we have proved <m>g_{r-1}(T)(v_i)=0</m>, where <m>1\leq i\leq r-1</m>. We show that <m>g_{r}(T)(v_i)=0</m> for all <m>1\leq i\leq r</m>. Since <m>g_r(T)=(T-\lambda_r\unit_V)g_{r-1}(T)</m>, we only need to show that <m>g_{r}(T)(v_{r})=0</m>.		We have 		<md>			<mrow>g_{r}(T)(v_{r})\amp=(T-\lambda_{r}\unit_V)g_{r-1}(T)(v_{r})\amp</mrow>			<mrow>\amp= g_{r-1}(T)(T-\lambda_{r}\unit_V)(v_{r})\amp\text{by}\; <xref ref="commutativity-general"/></mrow>			<mrow>\amp= g_{r-1}(T)\left(\sum_{\ell=1}^{r-1}a_{\ell r}v_\ell\right)\amp\text{by}\;<xref ref="matrix-representation"/></mrow>			<mrow>\amp=\sum_{\ell=1}^{r-1}a_{\ell r}g_{r-1}(T)(v_\ell)\amp\text{as}\;g_{r-1}(T)\in\End_F(V)</mrow>		</md>		By induction <m>g_{r-1}(T)(v_\ell)=0</m> for <m>1\leq\ell\leq r-1</m>. Hence, <m>g_{r}(T)(v_r)=0</m>. Hence the required result can be obtained by taking <m>r=n</m>.	</proof>	<p>Using Cayley-Hamilton theorem we show that a linear map <m>T\colon\R^3\to\R^3</m> has either a one-dimensional or a two-dimensional invariant subspace.</p>	<example xml:id="invariant-subspace-of-dim-1-or-2">		<title>(Invariant subspace of dimension <m>1</m> or <m>2</m> in <m>\R^3</m>)</title>		<statement>			<p>				Let <m>T\colon\R^3\to\R^3</m> be an <m>\R</m>-linear map. Then <m>T</m> has either a one-dimensional or a two-dimensional invariant subspace.			</p>			<p>				 Indeed, the characteristic polynomial of <m>T</m>, <m>\chi_T</m> is of the degree <m>3</m>. Hence <m>\chi_T</m> has a real root, say <m>a\in\R</m> (this can be proved, for instance, by using continuity of polynomial <m>\chi_T</m>). By <xref ref="criterion-for-root"/>, there exists a monic (i.e., coefficient of <m>t^2</m> is <m>1</m>) quadratic polynomial <m>q(t)\in\R[t]</m> such that 				<men xml:id="example-eq">\chi_T=(t-a)\cdot q(t)</men>				By Cayley-Hamilton Theorem, <m>T</m> is annihilated by the characteristic polynomial <m>\chi_T\in\R[t]</m>.				Hence, by <xref ref="ev-multiplication"/>, <me>0=\chi_T(T)(v)=(T-a\unit_{\R^3})\left(q(T)(v)\right)\quad\text{for all}\;v\in\R^3.</me>			</p>			<p>We now assume that <m>v\in\R^3</m> is a nonzero vector.</p>			<p>				<alert>Case 1</alert>. Suppose that <m>q(T)(v)\neq 0</m>. If we put <m>w=q(T)(v)\in\R^3</m> then <m>(T-a\unit_{\R^3})(w)=0</m>, i.e., <m>\langle w\rangle</m> is a one-dimensional subspace invariant under <m>T</m>.			</p>			<p>				<alert>Case 2</alert>. Suppose that <m>q(T)(v)= 0</m> and <m>q(t)=t^2+bt+c\in\R[t]</m>. Thus <m>(T^2+bT+c\unit_{\R^3})(v)=0</m>. Consider the subspace <m>W=\langle v,T(v)\rangle</m>. If 				<m>v</m> and <m>T(v)</m> are linearly dependent then <m>v</m> is an eigenvector of <m>T</m> and we are done. So we assume that <m>\dim_{\R}W=2</m>. Note that <m>T^2(v)=-bT(v)-cv\in W</m> and hence <m>W</m> is an invariant subspace of dimension <m>2</m>.				</p>	</statement>	</example></section>